%I A395588 #20 May 11 2026 09:22:48
%S A395588 1,1,2,4,6,10,14,22,44,82,112,126,170,204,298
%N A395588 Maximum orbit size of the topdrop map on permutations of the positive integers 1 through n.
%C A395588 The topdrop map is performed as follows: given a permutation of the integers 1 through n, look at the first entry, take the block from the start with as many elements as that entry, reverse the block and move it to the end. For example, suppose we want to apply the topdrop map to the permutation 416352. Since the permutation begins with 4, we take the first 4 elements, 4163, reverse them (3614) and move them to the end, which results in the permutation 523614.
%C A395588 The map is a bijection, so it partitions permutations of the integers 1 through n into distinct orbits. a(n) is the maximum orbit size.
%H A395588 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a395/A395588.java">Java program</a> (github)
%H A395588 Nathan R. Krause, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.16679">The Dynamics and Orbit Structure of the Topdrop Map</a>, arXiv preprint arXiv:2510.16679 [math.CO], 2025.
%e A395588 For n=4, the orbit of the permutation 2341 is 2341, 4132, 2314, 1432, 4321, 1234 which has size 6. Further, this is the maximum size for permutations of the positive integers 1 through 4, so a(4)=6. Multiple orbits of maximum size may exist, for example the orbit of 3142 also has size 6, and 3142 is not in the orbit above.
%K A395588 nonn,hard,more,new
%O A395588 0,3
%A A395588 _Nathan R. Krause_, Apr 29 2026
